The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
 Wednesday, August 04, 2004 				 Bolpur highway tag
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Calcutta, Aug. 3: The Centre has decided to develop the 60-km road linking Bolpur and Burdwan and accord it the status of a national highway.																								Union minister for roads and highways T.R. Baalu made an announcement to this effect today at Writers Buildings. The existing road is in bad shape and the project would cost about Rs 300 crore, he said.																								A feasibility study is on for a new expressway linking Calcutta, Kulpi and Harwood Point  the last patch of land before Sagar Island  Baalu added.																								The project involves connecting NH 34 at Amdanga with NH 41 at Haldia. This will also involve building a 3.2-km bridge over the Ganga at Kukrahati in Raichak, a public works department official said.																								The Union transport ministry is favourably considering the chief ministers demand to widen the two-lane NH 34 into a four-lane road, Baalu said.																								The Centre, the Union minister added, is keen to ensure that all state capitals are connected with the respective international boundaries.																								The state had submitted a proposal to link the 391-km road between Tuli on the Jhargram border to the Bangladesh border at Petrapole, PWD minister Amar Chowdhury said.																								Baalu said the Centre is seriously considering two of the states dream projects  a dock at Sagar Island and the much-hyped Sagarmala project.																								On his first trip here as the Union minister, Baalu said the change of Union government would not to affect work on projects that have been initiated. 
